</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[145,761,1094,1300]" pageId="18" pageNumber="689">
<emphasis box="[145,451,1094,1116]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="689">Morphology and anatomy:</emphasis>
Sponge formed by loosely anastomosed tubes (
<figureCitation box="[376,487,1125,1147]" captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="19.[163,241,1289,1311]" captionTargetBox="[163,1443,195,1249]" captionTargetId="figure-255@19.[163,1443,195,1249]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="Figure 9. Ascandra mascarenica (holotype; UFRJPOR 8936). A, specimen in vivo, living among other sponges, bryozoans, and hydrozoans. B, fixed specimen. C, cross-section of a tube (arrows point to diactines). D, tangential section of the surface." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6354316" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6354316/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="689">Fig. 9A, B</figureCitation>
). Large water-collecting tubes are present at the apical region (
<figureCitation box="[575,654,1156,1178]" captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="19.[163,241,1289,1311]" captionTargetBox="[163,1443,195,1249]" captionTargetId="figure-255@19.[163,1443,195,1249]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="Figure 9. Ascandra mascarenica (holotype; UFRJPOR 8936). A, specimen in vivo, living among other sponges, bryozoans, and hydrozoans. B, fixed specimen. C, cross-section of a tube (arrows point to diactines). D, tangential section of the surface." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6354316" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6354316/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="689">Fig. 9B</figureCitation>
). Surface hispid (
<figureCitation box="[230,311,1186,1208]" captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="19.[163,241,1289,1311]" captionTargetBox="[163,1443,195,1249]" captionTargetId="figure-255@19.[163,1443,195,1249]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="Figure 9. Ascandra mascarenica (holotype; UFRJPOR 8936). A, specimen in vivo, living among other sponges, bryozoans, and hydrozoans. B, fixed specimen. C, cross-section of a tube (arrows point to diactines). D, tangential section of the surface." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6354316" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6354316/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="689">Fig. 9C</figureCitation>
). Aquiferous system asconoid. Skeleton composed of tetractines of two sizes, diactines and few triactines (
<figureCitation box="[269,350,1248,1270]" captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="19.[163,241,1289,1311]" captionTargetBox="[163,1443,195,1249]" captionTargetId="figure-255@19.[163,1443,195,1249]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="Figure 9. Ascandra mascarenica (holotype; UFRJPOR 8936). A, specimen in vivo, living among other sponges, bryozoans, and hydrozoans. B, fixed specimen. C, cross-section of a tube (arrows point to diactines). D, tangential section of the surface." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6354316" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6354316/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="689">Fig. 9D</figureCitation>
). The diactines are perpendicular to the tubes.
</paragraph>
